      <!-- Section 1 -->
      <section id="why-travel-differs" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Why Travel &amp; Hospitality Differs in AI Search</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Travel is one of the sectors where AI search has displaced traditional search behaviour most rapidly.</strong>
          Users planning holidays, business trips, and short breaks are natural language users — they do not type "best hotels Lisbon" into a search bar;
          they ask "what are the best boutique hotels in Lisbon for a long weekend in September?" The conversational, multi-faceted nature of travel queries
          maps directly onto what generative AI does well.
        </p>

        <p>
          The consequence for travel brands is that AI search is not a future concern — it is a present one. A hotel group that holds the
          top three positions in traditional Google Search for its target keywords may be entirely absent from Google AI Overviews for the
          same destination queries if its entity data is incomplete or its content is not structured for extraction.
        </p>

        <p>
          Travel also has a distinctive query topology. Unlike B2B software or professional services, where queries are predominantly informational
          or commercial, travel mixes itinerary queries ("plan a 5-day trip to…"), comparison queries ("X hotel vs Y hotel"), recommendation queries
          ("best family-friendly resorts in…"), and booking research queries ("what is the baggage policy for…"). Each query type requires a different
          content structure to be citation-ready.
        </p>

        <p>
          This page is part of the <a href="/geo-by-industry/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO by Industry</a> series.
          For the foundational GEO framework that underpins all industry-specific guidance, see
          <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">Generative Engine Optimisation: The Complete Guide</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2 -->
      <section id="itinerary-queries" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>Itinerary &amp; Recommendation Queries</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>Itinerary and recommendation queries are the dominant AI search format in travel, and they require structurally different content from any other query type.</strong>
            When a user asks ChatGPT for a 7-day Japan itinerary, the model constructs a day-by-day plan by drawing on its parametric knowledge and,
            in RAG-enabled platforms, live retrieval of destination content. The brands cited — the hotels named, the airlines recommended,
            the experiences suggested — are those whose structured content most directly answers the underlying sub-questions.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-5">
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Day-by-Day Itinerary Pages</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Destination pages structured as day-by-day itineraries — with named locations, activity categories, and specific time allocations —
              are among the most cited content formats across all AI travel queries. The structure maps onto how AI systems generate itinerary
              responses: each day is a discrete retrieval unit. A page titled "7 Days in Kyoto: Day-by-Day Itinerary" with clearly marked
              day headings, named venues, and specific recommendations is significantly more retrievable than a generic "Things to Do in Kyoto" page.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Best-for Recommendation Pages</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              "Best for" pages — best hotels for families, best airlines for long-haul comfort, best destinations for solo female travellers —
              are consistently retrieved for recommendation queries. Each recommendation should lead with a bold declarative statement
              (the format AI systems extract most reliably) followed by specific supporting attributes: star rating, price tier,
              location relative to key landmarks, and at least one distinguishing characteristic.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Comparison and Booking Research Pages</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Booking research queries — "what is included in a premium economy seat on [airline]?", "what is the cancellation policy at [hotel]?" —
              are answered from structured, FAQ-format content. Brands that publish policy information in an explicit Q&amp;A structure,
              backed by FAQPage schema, appear in AI answers to policy queries. Brands that bury this information in dense terms-and-conditions
              pages do not.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3: Entity & Review Signals -->
      <section id="entity-signals" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>Entity &amp; Review Signals for Travel Properties</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>In travel, entity authority is built across a more distributed set of data sources than in most other sectors.</strong>
            A hotel's entity is not primarily defined by its own website — it is defined by the aggregate signal across Google Maps,
            TripAdvisor, Booking.com, Expedia, Wikidata, and dozens of other directories and review platforms. AI systems cross-reference
            these sources when deciding whether to cite a property and how to describe it.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-geo-800">
          <table class="w-full text-sm text-left">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-geo-800 bg-geo-900/60">
                <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-3 font-semibold text-ink-100">Signal Source</th>
                <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-3 font-semibold text-ink-100">What It Contributes</th>
                <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-3 font-semibold text-ink-100">Priority</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-geo-800">
              <tr class="hover:bg-geo-900/40 transition">
                <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-200 font-medium">Google Maps / Business Profile</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-300">Category, location, hours, amenities, review aggregate — feeds Google AI Overviews and Gemini directly</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 text-accent-400 font-semibold">Critical</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="hover:bg-geo-900/40 transition">
                <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-200 font-medium">TripAdvisor</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-300">Review volume, ranking within destination category, certificate of excellence signals</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 text-accent-400 font-semibold">Critical</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="hover:bg-geo-900/40 transition">
                <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-200 font-medium">Booking.com / Expedia</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-300">OTA presence validates the entity as a bookable property; rating scores contribute to authority assessment</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-300">High</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="hover:bg-geo-900/40 transition">
                <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-200 font-medium">Wikidata</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-300">Canonical entity identifier; feeds multiple AI training pipelines and knowledge graph lookups</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-300">High</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="hover:bg-geo-900/40 transition">
                <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-200 font-medium">Own site Review schema</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-300">AggregateRating markup surfacing review score and count to retrieval systems</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-300">Medium</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="hover:bg-geo-900/40 transition">
                <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-200 font-medium">Editorial mentions (Condé Nast, Lonely Planet, Frommer's)</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-300">High-authority citation signals that anchor the entity in travel category associations within training data</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 text-ink-300">Medium</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="prose-dark mt-8">
          <p>
            Review recency matters alongside volume. AI systems in RAG-enabled platforms retrieve live or recently cached content.
            A property with 2,000 TripAdvisor reviews but none in the past six months may score lower on freshness than a property
            with 400 reviews and consistent recent activity. Encouraging and responding to reviews is not just a reputation management
            task — it is an AI visibility signal.
          </p>
          <p>
            For a deeper treatment of entity signals and how to build them, see our guide to
            <a href="/ai-brand-visibility/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AI brand visibility</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4: Destination Content Strategy -->
      <section id="destination-content" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Destination Content Strategy for AI Visibility</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Destination content is the primary vehicle through which travel brands build AI citation authority.</strong>
          A hotel that publishes only its room types and booking pages gives AI systems almost nothing to retrieve for the itinerary and recommendation
          queries that dominate travel AI search. A hotel that publishes structured destination guides, neighbourhood profiles, and
          "best for" comparison content gives AI systems retrievable, citable content that associates the brand with the destination.
        </p>

        <h3>The Destination Content Stack</h3>
        <p>
          An effective destination content strategy for AI citation operates across three levels:
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Level 1 — Destination authority pages.</strong> Top-level guides to the destination itself ("The Complete Guide to Lisbon's Alfama District")
          establish topical authority and are retrieved for broad destination queries. These pages should answer the questions AI systems
          receive most frequently about the destination: when to go, how to get there, how long to stay, and what the key areas are.
          Each section should begin with a bold declarative statement that can be extracted standalone.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Level 2 — Category comparison pages.</strong> Pages comparing options within a category ("Boutique Hotels in the Bairro Alto: A Comparison")
          are retrieved for "best X in Y" queries. These work best as structured tables with consistent attributes — price tier, location,
          star rating, standout features — rather than as listicles with descriptive paragraphs.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Level 3 — Itinerary and experience pages.</strong> Specific day-by-day or experience-oriented pages ("3 Days in Porto: A Local's Itinerary")
          are retrieved for itinerary queries. Structuring these with explicit day headers and named properties makes them highly extractable
          for AI itinerary generation.
        </p>

        <h3>Structured Data for Travel Content</h3>
        <p>
          Beyond Article and FAQPage schema, travel properties should implement LodgingBusiness (for hotels), TouristAttraction, and
          AggregateRating markup. Airlines and transport providers should implement Airline and Flight schema where applicable.
          TouristDestination markup signals to AI retrieval systems that a page is authoritative about a specific place rather than
          incidentally mentioning it. These schemas are not widely adopted in the travel sector, which means early implementation
          creates a structural advantage over competitors who rely solely on text-based signals.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 5: Platform Breakdown -->
      <section id="platform-breakdown" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>Platform-by-Platform Breakdown for Travel</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>Each major AI platform has a different retrieval mechanism and different relevance to travel query types.</strong>
            A single strategy cannot optimise for all platforms simultaneously, but understanding the distinctions helps prioritise effort.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-geo-800">
          <table class="w-full text-sm text-left">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-geo-800 bg-geo-900/60">
                <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-3 font-semibold text-ink-100">Platform</th>
                <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-3 font-semibold text-ink-100">Primary Mechanism</th>
                <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-3 font-semibold text-ink-100">Travel Relevance</th>
                <th scope="col" class="px-5 py-3 font-semibold text-ink-100">Key Optimisation Action</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-geo-800">
